{#-
  Shared human-rendering policy for the count and diff tables.

  Everything a reader of the table actually reads is authored here or in the two
  templates that import this file (`count_table`, `diff_table`): the header
  words, the footer wording, the label column's width and truncation, the
  alternating-row semantics, and the semantic style tags. Rust ships typed
  numbers plus the facts below; it assembles no display strings and names no
  style.

  What is shared lives here; what is genuinely count- or diff-specific (numeric
  cells vs `+added/-removed/net` notation, and the per-column widths each
  implies) stays in the calling template, where it can be read in one place
  rather than reconstructed from a parameterised abstraction.

  Style tags are *semantic* — `[header]`, `[table_row_odd]`, `[additions]`,
  `[deletions]`, `[muted]` — and resolve through `styles/default.css`. Never
  write a raw ANSI sequence or a concrete colour here.

  A tag the theme does not define does NOT fail the render: text mode strips it
  and term-debug prints it verbatim, so it looks correct in both. Adding a tag
  here therefore means adding the matching rule to `styles/default.css` AND its
  name to `SEMANTIC_TAGS` in `src/pipeline_tests.rs` — that list is the only
  thing that notices. `table_row_odd` is the exception that needs no CSS rule:
  it comes from `Theme::default()`, adaptively.
-#}

{#- The label column's fixed display width. -#}
{%- set LABEL_WIDTH = 40 -%}

{#- Column key (a *data* name, as Rust ships it, matching the `Locs` field and
    the JSON/CSV schemas) -> the header word a human reads. This mapping is the
    reason Rust never needs to know a display word. -#}
{%- set COLUMN_HEADERS = {
      "code": "Code",
      "tests": "Tests",
      "examples": "Examples",
      "docs": "Docs",
      "comments": "Comments",
      "blanks": "Blanks",
      "total": "Total",
    } -%}

{#- Aggregation key -> the label column's header word. -#}
{%- set LABEL_HEADERS = {
      "total": "Name",
      "crate": "Crate",
      "module": "Module",
      "file": "File",
    } -%}

{#- Aggregation key -> the plural unit the footer counts. Total aggregation is
    absent on purpose: it counts files, not rows (see `footer_label`). -#}
{%- set UNITS = {
      "crate": "crates",
      "module": "modules",
      "file": "files",
    } -%}

{#- The horizontal rule, spanning the label column plus every value column and
    the single space that separates each. -#}
{%- macro rule(value_widths) -%}
{{ "─" * (LABEL_WIDTH + (value_widths | sum) + (value_widths | length)) }}
{%- endmacro -%}

{#- The footer's label.

    Four shapes, and the distinctions are deliberate:

    - Total aggregation counts *files*, because it has no rows to count.
    - When nothing was reduced, the count is plain.
    - "top X of Y" for `--top` (a sorted slice) vs plain "X of Y" for rows a
      filter eliminated: the wording has to stay honest about which happened,
      since only the former means "the biggest ones".
    - When a filter AND `--top` both reduced the rows, "top" wins, because the
      visible rows ARE the top of what passed the filter.

    In every case the totals row still describes the full data set, not the
    visible slice — which is exactly why the gap is spelled out rather than
    left for the reader to infer. -#}
{%- macro footer_label(aggregation, footer) -%}
{%- if aggregation == "total" -%}
Total ({{ footer.file_count }} files)
{%- elif footer.displayed == footer.total_items -%}
Total ({{ footer.total_items }} {{ UNITS[aggregation] }})
{%- elif footer.top_applied -%}
Total (top {{ footer.displayed }} of {{ footer.total_items }} {{ UNITS[aggregation] }})
{%- else -%}
Total ({{ footer.displayed }} of {{ footer.total_items }} {{ UNITS[aggregation] }})
{%- endif -%}
{%- endmacro -%}

{#- One data row.

    Alternating rows: even-indexed (1-based) rows get a [table_row_odd] wrap
    that paints the row background. Odd-indexed rows are emitted bare —
    wrapping them in [table_row_even] (an empty style in the default theme)
    causes standout-bbparser to strip the inner [additions]/[deletions]
    resets without emitting its own, which makes the last cell's fg colour
    bleed into the next row's label.

    Labels truncate at the *start* so the distinctive tail of a long path
    survives; values right-align so digits line up. -#}
{%- macro data_row(label, values, value_widths, index) -%}
{%- set line -%}
{{ label | col(LABEL_WIDTH, truncate='start') }}{% for v in values %} {{ v | col(value_widths[loop.index0], align='right') }}{% endfor %}
{%- endset -%}
{%- if index is even -%}
[table_row_odd]{{ line }}[/table_row_odd]
{%- else -%}
{{ line }}
{%- endif -%}
{%- endmacro -%}

{#- The table proper: header, rule, rows, rule, footer.

    `rows` and `total` carry cells that are already in their final display form
    — plain numbers for count, `+added/-removed/net` notation for diff — so this
    macro owns layout and owns no cell policy.

    The closing rule is suppressed when there are no rows, so a total-only table
    reads as one rule between header and total rather than two around nothing.

    Returns without a trailing newline; the caller places it. -#}
{%- macro table(aggregation, headers, rows, total, footer, value_widths) -%}
[header]{{ LABEL_HEADERS[aggregation] | col(LABEL_WIDTH, align='center') }}{% for h in headers %} {{ h | col(value_widths[loop.index0], align='right') }}{% endfor %}[/header]
{{ rule(value_widths) }}
{% for row in rows -%}
{{ data_row(row.label, row.values, value_widths, loop.index) }}
{% endfor -%}
{%- if rows | length > 0 -%}
{{ rule(value_widths) }}
{% endif -%}
{{ footer_label(aggregation, footer) | col(LABEL_WIDTH) }}{% for v in total %} {{ v | col(value_widths[loop.index0], align='right') }}{% endfor %}
{%- endmacro -%}
